  "articleSummary": "The article critiques the dogmatic application of the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), arguing that conflating \"small\" with \"cohesive\" leads to over-fragmented codebases. It warns against \"Single-Purpose People\" who prioritize atomic functions/files over meaningful modularity, creating issues like dependency tangles, brittle tests, and cognitive overload. Focusing on developers using frameworks like React/Redux, the author advocates for pragmatic SRP: grouping logically related code that *changes together*, rather than enforcing rigid atomicity. The tone is analytical and cautionary, using metaphors like \"file system shrapnel\" and \"Rube Goldberg architecture\" to highlight the chaos of extreme over-abstraction. The core thesis emphasizes balancing SRP with cohesion to maintain productivity and clarity.",
